Regarding Adorno, as Eric Pape says, as a pessimist not a cynic, not    
giving up the "ever more problematic possibility of Utopia." 
    
Can't one be a non-cynic, in fact can't one even be an optimist (but my     
that is harder every day) without believing in Utopia. Even Thomas More     
had his problems with Utopia, creating one which was patently unlivable,    
and putting its articulation in the utterings of Raphael Hythloday, a   
character whose name etymologically (and loosely, I believe) may be     
translated as "bringer of health/babbler of nonsense." Equivocal at the     
least.     
    
    charles alexander     
