Date:     Tue, 28 Feb 1995 12:16:41 EST      
Reply-To: UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>     
Sender:   UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>     
From:     Kali Tal <kalital@MERCURY.CIS.YALE.EDU>    
Subject:  Origin of term "backchannel"       
    
>backchannel (where did that term originate?)    
>communications    
>      
>lbd       
    
I picked up the term on the VWAR-L, a list populated by many military   
veterans as well as a certain percentage of wannabe veterans, fake vets, and    
interested others.  It was the first place I ever heard it, though      
everywhere I've used it, it's been picked up immediately because people like    
it (I like it; that's why I use it).  My in-house military consultant   
(business partner Steve Gomes, a Desert Storm-era vet) says it's a      
faux-military term based on the notion of switching to an alternate     
frequency, off the "command channel" or public frequency.  What makes it    
useful, I think, is that it emphasizes that there are "lines" or "channels" 
of communication in espace, different "frequencies" which are accessible to 
different audiences.   
    
Kali       
    
_______________    
    
    
Kali Tal   
Sixties Project & Viet Nam Generation, Inc.      
